            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this pediatric BSA dosing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you move from basic anthropometric data (height
                and weight) to a practical pediatric medication dose using both
                body surface area (BSA, in m²) and body weight (kg). It is
                designed for teaching, double-checking manual calculations, and
                comparing mg/m² vs mg/kg dosing.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Body surface area (BSA) formulas</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator supports three commonly cited BSA formulas. All
                return BSA in square meters (m²).
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Mosteller (default)</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{BSA}_{Mosteller} = \sqrt{\dfrac{\text{height (cm)}
                  \times \text{weight (kg)}}{3600}} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
                  Simple, widely used in pediatrics and oncology; good agreement
                  with more complex formulas.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">DuBois &amp; DuBois</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{BSA}_{DuBois} = 0.007184 \times \text{height
                  (cm)}^{0.725} \times \text{weight (kg)}^{0.425} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Haycock</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{BSA}_{Haycock} = 0.024265 \times \text{height
                  (cm)}^{0.3964} \times \text{weight (kg)}^{0.5378} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Dose calculations (mg/m² and mg/kg)</h3>
              <p>You can choose one or both dosing bases:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>mg/m² dosing</strong>: commonly used in oncology and
                  some high-risk medications.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>mg/kg dosing</strong>: widely used for general
                  pediatric medications.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">From mg/m² to mg</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Dose}_{mg} = \text{BSA (m²)} \times \text{Dose per m²
                  (mg/m²)} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">From mg/kg to mg</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Dose}_{mg} = \text{Weight (kg)} \times \text{Dose per
                  kg (mg/kg)} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                If you enter a <strong>maximum single dose</strong> (mg), the
                tool will:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Calculate the theoretical dose from BSA and/or weight.</li>
                <li>Compare it to the maximum dose.</li>
                <li>
                  Report both the theoretical dose and the capped dose, and flag
                  that capping occurred.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Converting mg to mL</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the drug concentration in mg/mL, the volume to
                administer is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \( \text{Volume (mL)} = \dfrac{\text{Dose
                  (mg)}}{\text{Concentration (mg/mL)}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator shows the volume for each calculated dose when a
                concentration is provided.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Consider a 6‑year‑old child, 110&nbsp;cm tall and 20&nbsp;kg in
                weight. The ordered dose is 75&nbsp;mg/m², with a maximum single
                dose of 400&nbsp;mg, and the drug concentration is
                10&nbsp;mg/mL.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Calculate BSA (Mosteller)</strong><br />
                  \( \text{BSA} = \sqrt{\dfrac{110 \times 20}{3600}} =
                  \sqrt{\dfrac{2200}{3600}} \approx \sqrt{0.6111} \approx 0.78\
                  \text{m²} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Calculate dose in mg</strong><br />
                  \( \text{Dose} = 0.78 \times 75 \approx 58.5\ \text{mg} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check against maximum dose</strong><br />
                  58.5&nbsp;mg is less than the 400&nbsp;mg maximum, so no
                  capping is needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Convert to mL</strong><br />
                  \( \text{Volume} = \dfrac{58.5}{10} \approx 5.85\ \text{mL} \)
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator performs all of these steps automatically and
                rounds results to a practical number of decimal places.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical caveats and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool does <strong>not</strong> know drug‑specific
                  pediatric limits, age cut‑offs or organ‑function adjustments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Neonates and premature infants often require
                  <strong>special dosing rules</strong> that are not captured by
                  simple BSA or mg/kg formulas.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For narrow‑therapeutic‑index drugs (e.g. chemotherapy, some
                  antibiotics, anticonvulsants), always cross‑check with:
                  <ul>
                    <li>An up‑to‑date pediatric formulary or protocol.</li>
                    <li>Renal and hepatic function.</li>
                    <li>Concomitant medications and clinical status.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                This calculator is for educational and decision‑support purposes
                only and is not a substitute for professional medical advice,
                diagnosis or treatment.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>When should I use BSA‑based dosing in pediatrics?</h3>
              <p>
                BSA‑based dosing is most common in pediatric oncology and some
                high‑risk medications where historical trials and protocols are
                expressed in mg/m². For many everyday drugs (antibiotics,
                analgesics, antipyretics), weight‑based dosing (mg/kg) is
                standard. Always follow the dosing method specified in your
                guideline or protocol.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why do different BSA formulas give slightly different values?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Each formula was derived from different populations and
                mathematical approaches. In most children, the differences
                between Mosteller, DuBois and Haycock are small (often
                &lt;5–10%). For consistency, institutions usually standardize on
                one formula.
              </p>

